Structure of a hypothesis test

Structure of a hypothesis test

  1. Start with a null hypothesis: An assumption on how the data is generated
  2. Based on this assumption, how likely were we to collect data as extreme as what we have?
    • p-value: probability of collecting data as extreme as ours (if null hypothesis is true)

Structure of a hypothesis test

  1. Start with a null hypothesis: An assumption on how the data is generated
  2. Based on this assumption, how likely were we to collect data as extreme as what we have?
    • p-value: probability of collecting data as extreme as ours (if null hypothesis is true)
  3. Is the p-value considered low or not?
    • Threshold should depend on the context
    • Typical threshold is 0.05 (there is a 5% chance of making a mistake)

Structure of a hypothesis test

  1. Start with a null hypothesis: An assumption on how the data is generated
  2. Based on this assumption, how likely were we to collect data as extreme as what we have?
    • p-value: probability of collecting data as extreme as ours (if null hypothesis is true)
  3. Is the p-value considered low or not?
    • Threshold should depend on the context
    • Typical threshold is 0.05 (there is a 5% chance of making a mistake)
  4. If p-value is below threshold, 2 possible conclusions:
    • A rare event just happened, or
    • Our assumption in Step 1 was false

mean(mpg for manual) = mean(mpg for automatic)

Is it true that cars with manual transmission consume the same amount of gas as automatic?

Hypothesis test: mtcars example

Is it true that cars with manual transmission consume the same amount of gas as automatic?

  1. p-value is below threshold, 2 possible conclusions:
    • A rare event just happened, or
    • Our assumption in Step 1 was false

We reject H0.

It is NOT true that

mean(mpg for manual) = mean(mpg for automatic)

It is NOT true that

cars with automatic transmission consume the same amount of gas as manual.

We are 95% sure!

How to get p-value: t-test

Good part: R will do all the computations for you.

What is a model?

A model is a simplified and idealized way to understand your data.

Linear model: \(child = a + b \cdot parent\).

Model (unknown) parameters:

  • \(a\) is intercept
  • \(b\) is slope

Many other possible models: linear without intercept, quadratic, exponential, …

Different models within the linear model family

Each line corresponds to a choice of \(a\) and \(b\).

Different models within the linear model family

What values of \(a\) and \(b\) are the best?

Which make the model match the data “most closely”.

What do we mean by “closely matching the data”?

We choose \(a\) and \(b\) such that minimize the sum of squares of the black lines below.

(Source: uc-r.github.io)

Linear models in R

  • Linear regression can be done with the lm function
  • Syntax: lm(formula, data = df)
  • Formulas look like y ~ x, which lm will translate to a function like \(y = a + b \cdot x\)
lm(child ~ parent, data = df)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = child ~ parent, data = df)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       parent  
##     41.0691       0.3842

Linear models in R

lm(child ~ parent, data = df)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = child ~ parent, data = df)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)       parent  
##     41.0691       0.3842
  • \(a = 41.0691\) is intercept
  • \(b = 0.3842\) is slope

Model: \(child = 41.0691 + 0.3842 \cdot parent\)

Interpretation: if parent’s height increases by one unit, the child gets higher by \(0.3842\) units.

Linear models in R

fit <- lm(child ~ parent, data = df)
coef(fit)
## (Intercept)      parent 
##   41.069105    0.384221
a <- coef(fit)[1]
b <- coef(fit)[2]

Linear models in R

Add the line to the plot via ggplot.

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = parent, y = child)) + 
    geom_point() + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = a, slope = b), 
                col = "blue", size = 1.5)

Linear models in R

Actually, ggplot has this option!

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = parent, y = child)) + 
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Linear models in R

You can can fit linear model to different categories.

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = parent, y = child)) + 
geom_point() +
facet_grid(par~chl)+
geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Prediction with regression

Suppose you know the parent’s height. You would like to predict how tall would be the child.

new_parent_heights <- data.frame(parent = c(65, 60, 71))
new_df <- new_parent_heights %>% mutate(child = a + b * parent)
new_df
##   parent    child
## 1     65 66.04347
## 2     60 64.12236
## 3     71 68.34879
predict(fit, newdata = new_parent_heights)
##        1        2        3 
## 66.04347 64.12236 68.34879

Prediction with regression

ggplot(data = df, aes(x = parent, y = child)) + 
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
    geom_point(data = new_df, aes(x = parent, y = child), color = "red")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
